{"author":{"id":"68dfa65ee618df2786e7da658bbfbbcc1f0c757170d9426e314e5f0886bcc55d"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1627486384,"nonce":"4vI8wG55DhdCPs2OJUjt4NVOPlI=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOAW4Y0s409Agy","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3848#issuecomment-888408114"},"message":"\u003e Hi @bernt-matthias\n\u003e \n\u003e Thanks for the message and details. It was interesting that the image said that the collection should be sorted after it is unzipped because I hadn't done this. I sorted the unzipped collection but I got the same result unfortunately.\n\nSorting the collections is only needed if they are not provided as pairs. Then the input collections might have different order  which would mix up samples. But in your workflow this seems fine.\n\n\u003e I also ran filterAndTrim before the forwards and reverse reads were unzipped. However, the filterAndTrim has the option to take paired collection data and the summary stats are the same for the R package so I think this is okay.\n\nThis is good. So we can focus on `learnErrors`.\n\n\u003e As far as I am aware, I have applied learnErrors and dada on the forward and reverse reads independently. See workflow here https://usegalaxy.eu/u/ollie_white/w/dada2-tutorial-pipeline for more details\n\nYes, the workflow looks good to me. I was just wondering because in one of the shared histories forward and reverse were used as inputs together.\n\n\u003e I noticed the parameter for the 'Magnitude of number of bases to use for learning'. I assumed this is the same as nbases in for the learnErrors command in R, which has a default value of 1e8. I left this as 8 to match the default for the R package. Note that I tried to increase this value in Galaxy but I got the same result again.\n\nWe set this as `10**8` here: https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/c2a498bd93a857c2c5bdd77d4974ed71235ad47a/tools/dada2/dada2_learnErrors.xml#L25 .. \n\n\u003e Would be great to know what you think? \n\nCan you share me a history that was created with the workflow. Then I can try to re-run `learnErrors` localy and provide the R code that is generated by the Galaxy tool. Then we can check for differences.\n\n\u003e I would like to use dada2 for a training course and I just want to make sure I can replicate the tutorial.\n\nOne question that I have in mind is if the numbers from the dada2 tutorial are up-to-date with the latest dada2 version?","files":null}]}